
ARP (Address Resolution Protocol)
🎯 Objective

Learn what ARP is, why it is needed, how it works, and how Linux uses ARP to communicate with devices on the same local network.

📖 What is ARP?

ARP (Address Resolution Protocol) is a network protocol used to find the MAC address of a device when its IP address is already known.

In simple words:

IP Address tells us "who" we want to reach, while ARP finds the MAC Address needed to actually deliver the data on the local network.

ARP operates only within a Local Area Network (LAN).

Why Do We Need ARP?

Suppose your computer wants to send data to:

IP Address

192.168.1.20

The computer knows the destination IP address but does not know the destination MAC address.

Since Ethernet communication requires MAC addresses, the computer first uses ARP to discover the MAC address.

How ARP Works
Step 1

Your computer wants to send data to:

192.168.1.20
Step 2

It checks the ARP Cache.

If the MAC address is already stored:

✔ Send data immediately.

If not:

Proceed to Step 3.

Step 3

Broadcast an ARP Request:

Who has 192.168.1.20?
Tell 192.168.1.10

Every device on the LAN receives this request.

Step 4

Only the device with IP:

192.168.1.20

responds:

My MAC Address is

00:1A:2B:3C:4D:5E
Step 5

The sender stores this information in its ARP Cache and sends the Ethernet frame using the discovered MAC address.


ARP Workflow Diagram

+-------------------+
| PC-A              |
| IP : 192.168.1.10 |
| MAC: AA:AA:AA     |
+-------------------+
          │
          │ ARP Request
          ▼
"Who has 192.168.1.20?"
          │
────────────────────────────── LAN
          │
          ▼
+-------------------+
| PC-B              |
| IP : 192.168.1.20 |
| MAC: BB:BB:BB     |
+-------------------+

ARP Reply:
"My MAC is BB:BB:BB"

The sender stores this information in its ARP Cache and sends the Ethernet frame using the discovered MAC address.


What is an ARP Cache?

An ARP Cache is a temporary table that stores mappings between IP addresses and MAC addresses.

This avoids sending an ARP request every time data needs to be transmitted.

Linux Commands
View ARP Cache
ip neigh

or

arp -a

Delete an ARP Entry
sudo ip neigh flush all

Show IP Address
ip addr

Test Connectivity
ping 192.168.1.20



Advantages of ARP
Automatically discovers MAC addresses.
Enables communication within a LAN.
Reduces manual configuration.
Stores mappings in cache for faster communication.
Limitations
Works only on local networks.
Broadcast requests increase network traffic.
Can be vulnerable to ARP Spoofing or ARP Poisoning attacks.


